<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>738</anchor> <rss>jms-00N3.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>jms-00N3</addr>  <route>jms-00N3.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Closure of <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injections</link> under <link href="jms-00II.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00II" title="The identity relation">identity</link> and <link href="jms-00IN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00IN" title="Relational composite">composition</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The <link href="jms-00KI.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KI" title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">identity function</link> is an <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injection</link> and the <link href="jms-00IN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00IN" title="Relational composite">composition</link> of <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injections</link> yields a <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injection</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
 <p>The <link href="jms-00KI.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KI" title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">identity function</link> is clearly <link href="jms-00KI.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KI" title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">injective</link>, as <tex>a_0=a_1</tex> implies <tex>a_0=a_1</tex>.</p>

 <p>Let <tex>f \colon  A \rightarrowtail  B</tex> and <tex>g \colon  B \rightarrowtail  C</tex> be <link href="jms-00M0.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00M0" title="The axiom of infinity">injections</link>. To show that the <link href="jms-00KI.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KI" title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">composite function</link> <tex>g \circ  f \colon  A \to  C</tex> is <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injective</link>, we fix <tex>a_0,a_1 \in  A</tex> to check that <tex>g { \mathopen {} \left ( f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_0 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}  = g { \mathopen {} \left ( f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_1 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> implies <tex>a_0=a_1</tex>. Because <tex>g</tex> is <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injective</link>, we have <tex>f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_0 \right ) \mathclose {}} =f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_1 \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>; therefore, because <tex>f</tex> is <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injective</link>, we have <tex>a_0=a_1</tex> as desired.</p>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>739</anchor> <rss>jms-00MN.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00MN</addr>  <route>jms-00MN.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>29</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Injective <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">functions</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>740</anchor> <rss>jms-00MO.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00MO</addr>  <route>jms-00MO.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>29</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Injection</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">function</link> <tex>f \colon  A \to  B</tex> is said to be <em><strong>injective</strong></em>, or an <em><strong>injection</strong></em>, whenever we have <tex>\forall  a_1,a_2 \in  A \mathpunct {.}  f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_1 \right ) \mathclose {}} =f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_2 \right ) \mathclose {}} \implies  a_1=a_2</tex>. Such a <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">function</link> is written <tex>f \colon  A \rightarrowtail  B</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>741</anchor> <rss>jms-00N1.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00N1</addr>  <route>jms-00N1.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title><link href="jms-00KS.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KS" title="Section-retraction pair">Sections</link> are <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injective</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Every <link href="jms-00KS.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KS" title="Section-retraction pair">section</link> is <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injective</link></p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
 <p>Let <tex>s \colon  B \to  A</tex> be a <link href="jms-00KS.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KS" title="Section-retraction pair">section</link> of <tex>r \colon  A  \to  B</tex>. Fixing <tex>b_1,b_2 \in  B</tex> such that <tex>s { \mathopen {} \left ( b_1 \right ) \mathclose {}} =s { \mathopen {} \left ( b_2 \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>, we must show that <tex>b_1=b_2</tex>. We have <tex>r { \mathopen {} \left ( s { \mathopen {} \left ( b_1 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}} =r { \mathopen {} \left ( s { \mathopen {} \left ( b_2 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> by assumption, and thus <tex>b_1=r { \mathopen {} \left ( s { \mathopen {} \left ( b_1 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}} =r { \mathopen {} \left ( s { \mathopen {} \left ( b_2 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}} =b_2</tex>.</p>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>742</anchor> <rss>jms-00N2.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00N2</addr>  <route>jms-00N2.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Subset inclusion are <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injective</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The function <tex>i_S \colon  S \to  A</tex> including a subset <tex>S \subseteq  A</tex> into <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injective</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
 Immediate: the inclusion maps a given element to itself!
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><p>Now that we have enough definitions in hand to see it, the import of <ref addr="jms-00M7" href="jms-00M7.xml" taxon="Theorem"/> is then to state that a <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">function</link> is <link href="jms-00KR.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KR" title="Bijection">bijective</link> if and only if it is both <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injective</link> and <link href="jms-00M8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00M8" title="Surjection">surjective</link>.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>743</anchor> <rss>jms-00N4.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>jms-00N4</addr>  <route>jms-00N4.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Counting <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injections</link> between <link href="jms-00LX.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00LX" title="Finite set">finite sets</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>For <link href="jms-00LX.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00LX" title="Finite set">finite sets</link> <tex>A</tex> and <tex>B</tex>, we can describe number of <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injections</link> from <tex>A</tex> to <tex>B</tex> as follows:</p><tex display="block">
  \mathord { \# } { \mathrm {Inj} { \mathopen {} \left ( A , B \right ) \mathclose {}} } =
  \begin {cases}
  { \mathord { \# } {B} \choose \mathord { \# } {A}} \cdot   { \mathopen {} \left ( \mathord { \# } {A} \right ) \mathclose {}} ! &amp; \text {when }  \mathord { \# } {A} \leq   \mathord { \# } {B}
   \\ 
  0 &amp; \text {otherwise}
  \end {cases}
</tex>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
 <p>We will argue from a combinatoric perspective.</p>

 <p>An <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injection</link> <tex>f</tex> from <tex>A</tex> to <tex>B</tex> associates no more than one <tex>a \in  A</tex> to the same <tex>b \in  B</tex>. Thus if we consider the subset <tex>U \subseteq  B</tex> spanned by elements of the form <tex>f { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>, we should then get a <link href="jms-00KR.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KR" title="Bijection">bijection</link> from <tex>A</tex> to <tex>U</tex>as each <tex>b \in  U</tex> comes from a <em>unique</em> <tex>a \in  A</tex>.</p>

 <p>Therefore, choosing an <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injection</link> amounts to making <em>two</em> independent choices: first we choose a subset of <tex>B</tex> that is in <link href="jms-00KR.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KR" title="Bijection">bijection</link> with <tex>A</tex>, and then we choose a <em>specific</em> <link href="jms-00KR.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KR" title="Bijection">bijection</link> from <tex>A</tex> to that subset. The number of such subsets is precisely <tex>\mathord { \# } {B} \choose   \mathord { \# } {A}</tex>, and we have already seen in <ref addr="jms-00KT" href="jms-00KT.xml" taxon="Proposition"/> that the number of such bijections is the factorial <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( \mathord { \# } {A}! \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>.</p>

 <p>Of course, if there is no subset of <tex>B</tex> equinumerous with <tex>A</tex>, then there can be no <link href="jms-00MO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00MO" title="Injection">injection</link>.</p>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>744</anchor> <rss>jms-00MO.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00MO</addr>  <route>jms-00MO.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>29</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Injection</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">function</link> <tex>f \colon  A \to  B</tex> is said to be <em><strong>injective</strong></em>, or an <em><strong>injection</strong></em>, whenever we have <tex>\forall  a_1,a_2 \in  A \mathpunct {.}  f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_1 \right ) \mathclose {}} =f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_2 \right ) \mathclose {}} \implies  a_1=a_2</tex>. Such a <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">function</link> is written <tex>f \colon  A \rightarrowtail  B</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>745</anchor> <rss>jms-00M0.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Axiom</taxon> <addr>jms-00M0</addr>  <route>jms-00M0.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>28</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The axiom of infinity</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The natural numbers form a set.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>746</anchor> <rss>jms-00KI.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>jms-00KI</addr>  <route>jms-00KI.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>22</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Closure of <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">functions</link> under <link href="jms-00II.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00II" title="The identity relation">identity</link> and <link href="jms-00IN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00IN" title="Relational composite">composition</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p><link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">Functions</link> are closed under <link href="jms-00II.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00II" title="The identity relation">identity</link> and <link href="jms-00IN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00IN" title="Relational composite">composition</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
 <p>We have already seen in <ref addr="jms-00K8" href="jms-00K8.xml" taxon="Theorem"/> that <link href="jms-00K7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00K7" title="Partial function">partial functions</link> are closed under <link href="jms-00II.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00II" title="The identity relation">identity</link> and <link href="jms-00IN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00IN" title="Relational composite">composition</link>. Therefore, it suffices to argue that the <link href="jms-00II.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00II" title="The identity relation">identity</link> <link href="jms-00K7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00K7" title="Partial function">partial function</link> is total, and that the <link href="jms-00IN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00IN" title="Relational composite">composition</link> of two <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">total</link> <link href="jms-00K7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00K7" title="Partial function">partial functions</link> is <link href="jms-00KF.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00KF" title="Function">total</link>.</p>

 <ol><li>We must show that for all <tex>a \in  A</tex>, there exists <tex>a'  \in  A</tex> such that <tex>a \mathrel { \mathsf {id}_{ A } } a'</tex>; unfolding the definition of the <link href="jms-00II.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00II" title="The identity relation">identity relation</link> we may choose <tex>a' = a</tex>.</li>
  <li>Given <tex>f \colon  A \to  B</tex> and <tex>g \colon  A  \to  C</tex>, we must check that for all <tex>a \in  A</tex>, there exists some <tex>c \in  C</tex> such that <tex>a \mathrel { { \mathopen {} \left ( g \circ  f \right ) \mathclose {}} }c</tex>. By the definition of <link href="jms-00IN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00IN" title="Relational composite">relational composition</link>, we must show that there exists <tex>b \in  B</tex> and <tex>c \in  C</tex> and such that <tex>a \mathrel {f}b</tex> and <tex>b \mathrel {c}</tex>. We choose <tex>b = f { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> and <tex>c = g { \mathopen {} \left ( b \right ) \mathclose {}} =g { \mathopen {} \left ( f { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>.</li></ol>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>747</anchor> <rss>jms-00IN.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00IN</addr>  <route>jms-00IN.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Relational composite</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Given <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relations</link> <tex>R \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</tex> and <tex>S \colon  B \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  C</tex>, we can define the <em><strong>relational composite</strong></em> <tex>S \circ  R \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  C</tex> in a way that generalises composition of functions. In particular, we define <tex>S \circ  R</tex> to be the following subset of <tex>A \times  C</tex>:</p><tex display="block">
  \begin {aligned}
 S \circ  R &amp; \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  C \\ 
  S \circ  R &amp;=
   { \mathopen {} \left \{ 
    { \mathopen {} \left ( a,c \right ) \mathclose {}} \in  A \times  C
    \mid 
    \exists  b \in  B \mathpunct {.} 
   a \mathrel {R}b  \land  b \mathrel {S} c
   \right \} \mathclose {}} 
  \end {aligned}
</tex></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>748</anchor> <rss>jms-00II.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00II</addr>  <route>jms-00II.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The identity <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>For any set <tex>A</tex>, we can form the <em><strong>identity <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em> <tex>\mathsf {id}_{ A } \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</tex>, also called the <em><strong>equality <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em>, which relates each element of <tex>A</tex> to itself. In other words, we have <tex>a \mathrel { \mathsf {id}_{ A } } a'</tex> if and only if <tex>a=a'</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>